		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/20/multimedia/motherlode-paternity2/motherlode-paternity2-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/20/multimedia/motherlode-paternity2/motherlode-paternity2-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/20/multimedia/motherlode-paternity2/motherlode-paternity2-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003754197" width="592" height="391" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="391"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Illustration by Abigail Gray Swartz</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//parenting.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/how-does-an-uber-driver-take-family-leave/" data-title="How Does an Uber Driver Take Family Leave?" data-description="More freelancers, contractors and entrepreneurs means even more people asking &quot;How am I going to take parental leave when my kid is born?&quot;">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My wife and I recently welcomed our first child, and throughout the pregnancy, I anxiously tried to settle on my plan for paternity leave. It seemed that every day, a new study or article came out that focused on the importance of fathers bonding with their newborn children and the ways corporate America was (or wasnât) stepping up to the plate to help. I understood all of this, but my new company, <a href="https://www.fatherly.com">Fatherly</a>, was barreling toward launch, and I wasnât sure how to fulfill my obligations to my work and my new family at the same time. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As someone born in the 80s, who defines âcareerâ in a very different way from my fatherâs generation, Iâm not alone in this anxiety. According to <a href="//blog.barkleyus.com/2013/07/17/the-millennial-generation-becomes-parents/">one report</a>, 80 percent of the four million babies born in 2013 were born to millennials, and as a generation, we have made freelancing, independent contracting and entrepreneurship a cornerstone of our careers. The next five years are expected to see 40 percent of the work force â 60 million people â <a href="//qz.com/65279/40-of-americas-workforce-will-be-freelancers-by-2020/">become independent workers</a> in some capacity. Some of these people will be entrepreneurs, but a lot more of them will be Airbnb hosts or Instacart shoppers or freelance code writers or baristas. What do they do when they or their partner has a baby? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We live in a country where the only federal protection for a parent who wants to take leave when their child is born is the Family Medical Leave Act, a toothless piece of legislation that simply forbids a company larger than 50 people from firing an employee who takes up to six weeks of unpaid time off for family reasons. Everything else is at the discretion and the whim of company policies. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Worse, when we leave parental leave up to businesses, we exclude all those businesses of one, and the innovative businesses structured around contractors. Even if Uber, Airbnb or other companies in the so-called sharing economy wanted to offer benefits, they couldnât without converting their contracted work force to employees and fundamentally altering their business models, which is something Uber may yet be forced to do <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/06/18/business/uber-contests-california-labor-ruling-that-says-drivers-should-be-employees.html?_r=0">by the California Labor Commission</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We can lament the end of the social welfare net that weâve forced businesses to provide in this country for the last three generations, but itâs irreparably damaged. Thatâs part of the reason we have more freelance workers, more dual income families in the first place, and why so many of us are asking, âHow am I going to take parental leave when my kid is born?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Perhaps the answer will be found in organizations like the Freelancers Union and Peers.org, which do good work trying to wrangle certain kinds of workers under a single umbrella and negotiate for things like health insurance. âMutual Aidâ business models are springing up, testing concepts like sick leave pools for Airbnb hosts. Co-working spaces are starting to offer child care. These are creative solutions that will create blueprints on which we can expand.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Or perhaps the answer will be found in government. California has already bested the F.M.L.A. with its own <a href="//paidfamilyleave.org/ask-us/what-is-paid-family-leave">Paid Family Leave policy</a> that provides workers who pay into the stateâs disability insurance fund 55 percent of their salary for six weeks. A program like this on the national level would go a long way to replacing, and even improving on, whatâs available to salaried workers in many instances. And it would provide freelance workers an option where currently they have none.  It seems as if the federal government is finally coming around. The Labor Department just issued a policy brief entitled &#8220;<a href="//www.dol.gov/asp/policy-development/PaternityBrief.pdf">Paternity Leave: Why Parental Leave Is So Important For Working Families.</a>&#8221; The report summarizes a lot of existing data on paternity leave and is a nice resource for those advocating on behalf of paternity leave for freelance workers â but it&#8217;s not as nice as government-backed options would be. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Whatever policy or free market solutions we devise in the coming years, theyâll be only part of the answer. The other part requires a cultural shift in how we prioritize and value parenting.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As I tried to figure out what I could reasonably do for paternity leave, I asked my peers who have children how they handled it, and I posed the question on Quora and Reddit. âGood entrepreneurs make bad fathers,â one business owner told me. âIf I donât work, I donât get paid,â said a freelance worker. These responses to the birth of our children arenât honorable or even pragmatic â all the evidence points to paid paternity leave being a huge net positive for societies and economies. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last year&#8217;s <a href="https://www.fatherly.com/should-you-take-more-time-off--1073233035.html">annual report on fatherhood</a> from Boston College&#8217;s Center for Work and Family rounded up multiple examples of this from abroad: In Britain, there&#8217;s strong correlation between paternity leave and a mother&#8217;s overall health at three months, postpartum; in Norway, paternity leave reduces missed work days for mothers by 5 percent to 10 percent; in France, it reduces postpartum depression; and in Sweden, it increases the mother&#8217;s earnings by 6.7 percent. The report found that 85 percent of United States companies surveyed found âno business caseâ for offering paternity leave; itâs a naivete that boggles the mind. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As a self-employed new father, I give myself a B-minus for how I handled paternity leave. I spent two weeks away from the office and devoted large swaths of every day to my wife and child. But I also spent hours online, answering emails and contributing to the build of our new site. It gave me an intimate understanding of whatâs really at stake as my generation enters into its own baby boom.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At Fatherly we now have a sample size of two when it comes to paternity leave â our editorial director had his first child a few months before me, and together we&#8217;ve experienced first hand how tricky it is to balance a proper leave and the chaos of a start-up without even the (meager) safety net of F.M.L.A. We&#8217;re taking what we&#8217;ve learned as new fathers in this new economy and are working hard to create parental leave policies that empower our future employees to be active and engaged parents and partners. </p>
<footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	    </div>
</footer>
